The Al-Aqsa Flood in the perspective of the Islamic philosopher and thinker A. Dr.. Taha Abdel Rahman

In the name of God, the most gracious, the most merciful

I got to know our professor, thinker and philosopher, Taha Abdel Rahman, through his works, many of which I read and reviewed, and which were the subject of discussion and reflection with acquaintances, friends, professors, and students. I met him for the first time in the year 2017 AD on the sidelines of the conference “Religion and Civilization: Preserving Urbanism is a Legal Purpose,” which I organized. Al-Furqan Foundation for Islamic Heritage, in partnership with Ibn Khaldun University in Istanbul.

Then personal contact with our professor Al-Falislov was renewed over the previous years through some correspondence and communications, and I tried to visit him last year, but his health condition prevented this.

During the past few days, on my second visit to Rabat, I called back to have his honorable wife answer me and apologize for his health condition, which had worsened after he underwent surgery during the past months.

Not a few minutes passed until the professor himself came back to me, welcoming the visit because he had asked to visit him from Gaza. As soon as I met him and his brother, the Moroccan scientist Dr. Muhammad Awam, he hugged me and said that I wanted to smell the fragrance of the Al-Aqsa flood through this meeting.

For more than an hour, we exchanged conversations and discussions about this battle, and these conversations were not devoid of what our professor required of himself in writing: investing in the graphic power of the Arabic tongue, and using the tools of logic in analyzing ideas.

These luminous philosophies of our professor can be enumerated as a new chapter to be added to his wonderful book, Thaghour al-Murabitah, in light of his fiduciary theory, which appeals to nature, morals, and ideals in studying the existential challenges facing the Arab and Islamic nation.

The cultural meaning of the Al-Aqsa flood:

Dr. Taha Abdel Rahman believes that the Al-Aqsa flood is a new resumption of civilization, a new revival of the nation, and a new birth for man, through new values ​​in which a person discovers himself and dives into its depths, connecting his appearance to his interior, and his immediate life to his future, and new concepts in which he feels his freedom in light of the prevalence of values ​​​​of worshiping the will. Israel, and new conditions under which he regains his nature in a reality in which misguided values ​​are widespread.

He adds: Today, the Palestinian resistance writes the history of the nation, and leads humanity towards the light with the minds that are opened by its own creation, and the self-reflections that have occurred and will occur as a result of its amazing action: individual and collective. It is truly a rational resumption of continuous giving, and a creative inheritance of renewable energy in the paths of Islamic and human history.

Although they are few in number, they are of great trustworthiness and noble will, because they re-establish values ​​on divine attributes, re-establish Islam on the sacred character, and re-establish the spirit on divine closeness, and the survival of the nation today and tomorrow depends on the survival of the resistance, and its defeat, God forbid, is a sign. With the annihilation of the nation.

The flood of Al-Aqsa is a horizon for reading the Battle of the Parties:

The thinker Abd al-Rahman al-Aqsa likens the flood of al-Aqsa to the Battle of the Parties that the Prophet, may God’s prayers and peace be upon him, and his companions fought, in which they faced the armies of the polytheists and Jews who surrounded the city from the outside, and the hypocrites and sick-hearted people who spread turmoil within it, until the hearts reached the throats.

Our professor, may God protect him, says: I saw this battle through the good preparation and planning that these mujahideen did, and the innovation of means of attack and defense, despite the limited capabilities and great challenges.

“One has no second in this time.” The Palestinian resistance in the imagination of the philosopher:

Our professor believes that resistance is the act that contributes to building Islamic civilization and building human civilizations.

He adds that the way our nation today can contribute to building civilization and human renewal is jihad, and not any other way, and for this contribution to see the light, a group of the nation must bear responsibility for it.

According to the philosopher, the vigilant Palestinian resistance man rose to carry this trust brilliantly, and bore this responsibility with benevolence. He carried it in the best way, and carried it out in the best way. In fact, he is one and has no second in this time.

“I have never achieved this meaning before.” Resistance is an existential, not political, act:

Resistance, from the perspective of the philosopher, is not a partial act, but rather a comprehensive act. He adds: I looked at resistance from an existential perspective, and I mean that there is no meaning to existence without resistance and no meaning to life without jihad. Because existence and life are gained from the act of resistance itself.

The resisting action provokes and brings together all the human capabilities of hearing, sight, reason, and all of the human senses. No specific organ or perception is unique to resistance. Jihad is not an act in which one of the faculties stops or is dominated by one of the faculties, but rather it is a willingness that uses all the faculties, and through it a person is formed in the truth.

Resistance and jihad in this sense are the elixir of life that God has granted to the resistors, and without it there is nothing but death and annihilation, as God Almighty said: {O you who have believed, respond to God and to the Messenger when he calls you to give you life } [Al-Anfal: 24], and it is also the characteristic that distinguishes him. The resistance fighters who left The justifications for incapacity, the reasons for sitting, and the motives for negativity on the part of all created beings, other than those who accepted betrayal and were accustomed to disappointment, so they were more like the dead than the living. And in this striving group, the saying of God Almighty is true: His likeness is in the darkness, not outside . Among them } [Al-An’am: 122].

Our professor believes that this comprehensive meaning has never been achieved before in explaining resistance, as an existential act that advances human existence itself.

“The Zionist mind has been defeated.” The philosopher’s dream came true:

Our professor told us that his political awareness and illusions began with the defeat of 1967 AD. At that time, he was a student at the university who was inclined towards writing poetry. This war caused a severe earthquake in him, and a fateful question seized upon him, which was: What is this mind that was able to defeat all the Arabs? How can a nation so numerous and well-established in its history be defeated? He has always had this question and this wish: When will we have a mind that will defeat the Zionist mind?

He adds: I carried these questions, which are questions of time and questions of the nation, as personal concerns and cognitive stakes, and I directed my studies towards logic and thought in order to discover the mental mechanisms by which the Zionist victory was achieved, and the defects and shortcomings due to which the Arab defeat occurred, and the echo of these questions continues to swell within me with Days passed until I saw the Palestinian fighter creating this flood, and I saw with my own eyes how the Zionist mind was defeated, so I felt for the first time the healing of my chest, and I got the answers to those questions that I had been straining in my cognitive gap in order to find them.

I believe that the greatest manifestation of the Arab and Islamic mind in the modern era is what was embodied in the flood of Al-Aqsa, where the capabilities of the Islamic mind were revealed to this resistor and he discovered its breadth and strength, and the capabilities of the Zionist mind were revealed to him and he discovered its limitations and fragility, so he took practical responsibility towards these facts, and these remarkable achievements were achieved with him. This is the meaning of selection from God Almighty.

The mind of the resistor is the mind of the supporter:

Taha Abd al-Rahman divides minds into three: an abstract mind hindered by limits, a guided mind interfered with by defects, and a supportive mind that swims in perfections.

The philosopher believes that the secret behind this success, which was achieved on October 7, is the mind supported by God.

He adds: This mind is filled with pure faith, transcending all limits of matter and purposes, and it rises like a king, with no disobedience remaining “light upon light.”

These fighters were and still are lights that shine in all of humanity with the values ​​that modern man has lost, in which he discovers his innate nature on the day when God makes him witness to his divinity, so that it will be revealed to him in its clearest and most beautiful form.

These fighters are heavenly, their determination has no limits in time or place, and is attached to the throne, and they are under the divine shadow. They gather and separate against God, and the angels fight with them.

What they achieved in three hours is proof that they are an example of the supportive mind that I have always talked about in my books and lectures, so blessed are they.

This is clear proof and a clear fact that God Almighty wanted to bequeath to them this divine preference and divine specialness, so that it would be a sign for those who had a heart or listened while being a witness, since what is important is taking this event into consideration, for it is a sign before it is a story.

“I wish I were young so I could fight with them!” “The philosopher’s wish in the battle of the flood.”

In an luminous moment in this luminous meeting, our professor revealed to us his feelings and his wish for this battle. He said: I wish I were a young man fighting with them. This is the time that deserves to live, and these are the moments that should be seized, moments of closeness to life that a person does not wish for another life. The divine speech is revealed to the fighter in it. He hears it as an addressee, not as a reader of a message. In these moments, if he supplicates, he is answered, and if he asks for forgiveness, he is forgiven. God’s support stays with him and does not depart from him, as God Almighty said: {If God helps you, none can defeat you} [Al Imran: 160 ] . And as he said: { How many small groups have defeated a large group, God willing } [Al-Baqarah: 249]. This is the moment I had hoped for in this battle in my life, but it was for this chosen sect.

“I was drawn to this book.”.. the motivation for classifying the book Thughoor Al-Marabat..

“I have always felt that there is a duty upon me that I must fulfill, otherwise my life would have lost its meaning, and I would have disobeyed God as I have disobeyed Him before. I am charged with this book, and I gave it to the publishing house without any right or reward.” “.

With these words, our professor, the thinker, may God protect him, summarized the story of the writing of the book Thaghour Al-Marabat, and the motivation for its classification, a reason he did not mention in the introduction to the aforementioned book.

In it, the dimensions of individual, cognitive, cultural, intellectual, and philosophical responsibility that worked in the philosopher’s soul are evident as a responsibility, a task, and a duty that cannot be neglected, otherwise these words lose their connotations and credibility.

Betrayal and normalization...betrayal of trust and betrayal of culture:

Our professor Taha Abdel Rahman conveyed to us his deep sadness and pain over the failure of the nation in general and its intellectuals in particular.

Among what he said: The nation’s failure is heartbreaking, especially the failure of intellectuals, and I consider that a large number of intellectuals have betrayed the trust and betrayed the culture.

Without normalization, the occupying state would not have done what it did, and if the normalizing countries had taken a stance, these criminal attacks would have stopped.

Regarding the required duty, the philosopher believes that the duty owed to the new generations is double the duty imposed on the previous generations.

The reason behind this is that what was said in 1967 AD was that the Jews had returned to their homeland, but today’s youth did not live those moments of defeat in which the extremism and fanaticism of the occupying state prevailed. Rather, they carry new perceptions accompanied by different preparations.

When the philosopher singles out the nation’s youth in his speech, it is due to his confidence that they are the secret of life in every society and nation, and that they are the only ones capable of bringing nations out of their darkness into the lights of reformist awareness and the brightest rising life.

Conclusion

Through this fiduciary philosophical contemplation and mystical moral reflection that transcends the apparent appearance of events to their inner meaning, it is possible to sense the civilizational horizons and moral elements of the Al-Aqsa Flood Battle within the intellectual project that occupied our professor Taha Abdel Rahman for decades, and I believe that the contemporary Muslim mind must reread its heritage in light of this concern. Burning within himself, burning in his mind, present in his memory, as it is not possible to separate the author’s intellectual contribution from his biography, and it is not possible to accurately gain insight into his desires and ideas apart from his concerns and goals.

In these deep thoughts mixed with sensitive feelings, the concept of responsibility towards the major events facing the nation was evident, to be a criterion for the truthfulness or falsity of the idea, and a witness to the life or death of the intellectual, so that with the flood of Al-Aqsa, the definition of thought and culture, duty and honesty would be redefined, and the mind would be renewed with it, and the spirit would be awakened with it. Modernity builds with it, because this construction and renewal depend on the jihadi resistance act.
